      @{"LAYOUT_WeightBar" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/gadgets/layout.h/File" 237} (@{"BOOL" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/exec/types.h/File" 91}) (V43.1)
          Place a user adjustable weighting bar here (ie; balance group bar).
          Bugs: Before 45.9 @{"LAYOUT_WeightBar" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/gadgets/layout.h/File" 237} didn't work correctly when used
          in the root layoutgroup because the render request on @{"SELECTUP" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/intuition.h/File" 1536} was
          rejected by window.class. Possible workarounds for this bug are:
                  a) Don't use @{"LAYOUT_DeferLayout" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/gadgets/layout.h/File" 152}
                  b) set @{"WFLG_NOCAREREFRESH" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/intuition.h/File" 1050}
                  c) don't add the weightbar to the rootlayout, instead add
                     a "dummy" group to the rootlayout that contains all the
                     children and the weightbar.

          Applicability is (@{"OM_NEW" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/classusr.h/File" 63}, @{"OM_SET" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/classusr.h/File" 65})


      Attributes referring to the "current" child object:

      @{"CHILD_MinWidth" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/gadgets/layout.h/File" 246}, @{"CHILD_MinHeight" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/gadgets/layout.h/File" 251} (@{"ULONG" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/exec/types.h/File" 52})
          The minimum width and height of the object, in pixels. Setting
          this attribute means that @{"GM_DOMAIN" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/gadgetclass.h/File" 323} is not respected in that
          direction.

          Defaults to ~0, which means that the layout gadget will ask the
          object, using @{"GM_DOMAIN" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/gadgetclass.h/File" 323}.

          Applicability is (@{"OM_NEW" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/classusr.h/File" 63}, @{"OM_SET" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/classusr.h/File" 65}, @{"OM_UPDATE" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/classusr.h/File" 70})

      @{"CHILD_MaxWidth" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/gadgets/layout.h/File" 260}, @{"CHILD_MaxHeight" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/gadgets/layout.h/File" 265} (@{"ULONG" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/exec/types.h/File" 52})
          As above, for the maximum size.

          Applicability is (@{"OM_NEW" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/classusr.h/File" 63}, @{"OM_SET" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/classusr.h/File" 65}, @{"OM_UPDATE" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/classusr.h/File" 70})

      @{"CHILD_NominalSize" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/gadgets/layout.h/File" 256} (@{"BOOL" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/exec/types.h/File" 91})
          If this attribute is @{"TRUE" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/exec/types.h/File" 95}, layout will use @{"GDOMAIN_NOMINAL" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/gadgetclass.h/File" 489}
          instead of @{"GDOMAIN_MINIMUM" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/gadgetclass.h/File" 486} when requesting the minimum size of
          the gadget. This is useful when the minimum size of a gadget
          looks unattractive, but the gadget will return a more attractive
          size with @{"GDOMAIN_NOMINAL" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/gadgetclass.h/File" 489}.

          Defaults to @{"FALSE" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/exec/types.h/File" 98}.

          Applicability is (@{"OM_NEW" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/classusr.h/File" 63}, @{"OM_SET" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/classusr.h/File" 65}, @{"OM_UPDATE" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/classusr.h/File" 70})

      @{"CHILD_WeightedWidth" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/gadgets/layout.h/File" 270} (@{"ULONG" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/exec/types.h/File" 52})
          The relative width of the child object. See the DESCRIPTION
          above for the layout method. If set to 0, the child will always
          be rendered in the minimum size (specified by either @{"GM_DOMAIN" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/gadgetclass.h/File" 323}
          or @{"CHILD_MinWidth" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/gadgets/layout.h/File" 246}). Use @{"CHILD_MinWidth" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/gadgets/layout.h/File" 246} and a weighted with of 0
          instead of @{"CHILD_MinWidth" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/gadgets/layout.h/File" 246} and @{"CHILD_MaxWidth" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/gadgets/layout.h/File" 260}. The latter method
          will also work, but will slow down the layout. As a special
          rule, many BOOPSI images using bitmap data can not be resized
          from the initial size. Fix their size by setting MinWidth and
          MinHeight, and the weight to 0.

          Defaults to 100.

          Applicability is (@{"OM_NEW" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/classusr.h/File" 63}, @{"OM_SET" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/classusr.h/File" 65}, @{"OM_UPDATE" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/classusr.h/File" 70})

      @{"CHILD_WeightedHeight" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/gadgets/layout.h/File" 273} (@{"ULONG" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/exec/types.h/File" 52})
          The relative height of the child object. See @{"CHILD_WeightedWidth" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/gadgets/layout.h/File" 270}.

          Applicability is (@{"OM_NEW" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/classusr.h/File" 63}, @{"OM_SET" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/classusr.h/File" 65}, @{"OM_UPDATE" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/classusr.h/File" 70})

      @{"CHILD_WeightMinimum" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/gadgets/layout.h/File" 301} (@{"BOOL" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/exec/types.h/File" 91})
          Setting this tag to @{"TRUE" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/exec/types.h/File" 95} will make the layout group set the
          weighted width and height to the minimum values set with
          @{"CHILD_MinWidth" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/gadgets/layout.h/File" 246} and @{"CHILD_MinHeight" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/gadgets/layout.h/File" 251} or returned by @{"GM_DOMAIN" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/gadgetclass.h/File" 323}. This
          allows creating layout groups where the relative size of the
          objects always remains the same. Be warned that if the object
          does not support @{"GM_DOMAIN" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/gadgetclass.h/File" 323} and minimum size is not set manually,
          the weight will be set to 2 (the default minimum size of an
          object). Normally you would want to set this tag for every
          resizable object in a layout group.

          Defaults to @{"FALSE" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/exec/types.h/File" 98}.

          Applicability is (@{"OM_NEW" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/classusr.h/File" 63})

      @{"CHILD_ReplaceObject" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/gadgets/layout.h/File" 288}
          @{"CHILD_ReplaceImage" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/gadgets/layout.h/File" 292} (Object *)
          Replace the current child object with the one specified. The
          current object will be disposed of. See @{"LAYOUT_AddChild" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/gadgets/layout.h/File" 128},
          @{"LAYOUT_AddImage" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/gadgets/layout.h/File" 131}, @{"LAYOUT_RemoveChild" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/gadgets/layout.h/File" 124}, @{"LAYOUT_ModifyChild" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/gadgets/layout.h/File" 135}.

          Applicability is (@{"OM_SET" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/classusr.h/File" 65})

      @{"CHILD_CacheDomain" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/gadgets/layout.h/File" 296} (@{"BOOL" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/exec/types.h/File" 91})
          To speed up resizing, layout gadget will normally cache the
          first values returned by @{"GM_DOMAIN" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/gadgetclass.h/File" 323} and use that cache for
          subsequent relayouts, instead of calling @{"GM_DOMAIN" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/gadgetclass.h/File" 323} again.
          Normally this will have the same results all the time. If you
          have a custom gadget that might return varying values between
          calls to @{"GM_DOMAIN" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/gadgetclass.h/File" 323} (ie the minimum or maximum size of it could
          vary during runtime), set this tag to @{"FALSE" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/exec/types.h/File" 98} for that object and
          all its parent groups. Note that since layout groups are aware
          of their parent layouts, they can disable caching in the
          hierarchy above them automatically,  if you SetAttr this
          attribute _AFTER_ creating the whole layout hierarchy.

          Defaults to @{"TRUE" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/exec/types.h/File" 95}.

          Applicability is (@{"OM_NEW" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/classusr.h/File" 63}, @{"OM_SET" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/classusr.h/File" 65}) (@{"OM_SET" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/classusr.h/File" 65} preferred)

      @{"CHILD_Label" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/gadgets/layout.h/File" 305} (Object *)
          The imageclass object, preferably label.image, to use as the
          object's label. These labels are supported only left or right
          aligned groups, and will be placed in the left or right of the
          gadget even in horizontal groups. All the labels will take the
          space of the widest label. Label-less objects will be laid out
          in full width; if you want to leave the label column empty, use
          the special value @{"LCLABEL_NOLABEL" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/gadgets/layout.h/File" 327}. Every object in a group gets
          the same amount of space reserved for a label, whether they have
          a label or not. This also (or in particular) applies to
          horizontal groups; usually the correct effect is reached by
          putting the label on the group itself instead of one of the
          objects in it. See @{"LAYOUT_LabelColumn" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/gadgets/layout.h/File" 188}.

          Defaults to @{"NULL" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/exec/types.h/File" 101}.

          Applicability is (@{"OM_NEW" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/classusr.h/File" 63}, @{"OM_SET" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/classusr.h/File" 65})

      @{"CHILD_NoDispose" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/gadgets/layout.h/File" 308} (@{"BOOL" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/exec/types.h/File" 91})
          By setting this attribute, you inform the layout object that
          this child object should not be automatically disposed when
          the layout object itself is disposed. This attribute allows
          sharing objects between layouts.

          Default is @{"FALSE" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/exec/types.h/File" 98}.

          Applicability is (@{"OM_NEW" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/classusr.h/File" 63}, @{"OM_SET" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/classusr.h/File" 65})

      CHILD_ScaledWidth (@{"UWORD" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/exec/types.h/File" 55}) (V42.27)
          Scales the child minimum domain size to a larger value;

          minwidth = minwidth + ((minsize * scalewidth)/100)

          Default is 0.

          Applicability is (@{"OM_NEW" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/classusr.h/File" 63}, @{"OM_SET" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/classusr.h/File" 65})

      CHILD_ScaledHeight (@{"UWORD" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/exec/types.h/File" 55}) (V42.27)
          Scales the child minimum domain size to a larger value;

          minheight = minheight + ((minsize * scaleheight)/100)

          Default is 0.

          Applicability is (@{"OM_NEW" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/classusr.h/File" 63}, @{"OM_SET" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/classusr.h/File" 65})

  NOTES
      Setting the attributes via @{"SetGadgetAttrs()" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/intuition/SetGadgetAttrsA"} (@{"OM_SET" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/classusr.h/File" 65}) will not
      automatically rerender the display! Call @{"RethinkLayout()" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/layout_gc/RethinkLayout"} to
      relayout and refresh display after @{"SetGadgetAttrs()" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/intuition/SetGadgetAttrsA"}.

      In this document, the terms layout, group, and object are used
      intermixed. Most of the time, layout and group are used as
      synonyms. Virtually any object referred to could also be a
      layout group.

      To make defining layout hierarchies easier, the reaction_macros.h
      include file defines a set of macros that hide @{"NewObject()" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/intuition/NewObject"}
      calls. This will clean up the rather large tag lists for the
      creation of layout groups. See the ReAction examples for use of
      these macros, and layout.gadget in general.

      In relation to above, remember that in AmigaOS (as of V40), the
      stack size is restricted. During the beta test period, the
      average size of a layout group for a whole window seemed to
      average at approximately 1 KB. Building as large tag lists as
      this on stack is rather slow, as well as easily overflowing the
      small default stacks of AmigaOS. For windows with relatively
      static layouts that are opened often, consider building tag
      lists as static data and passing a pointer to them for
      @{"NewObjectA()" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/intuition/NewObject"}. If this is too much work, make sure that your
      program's stack is large enough to hold  the tag list. If it is
      too small, you can use the V37 Exec @{"StackSwap()" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/exec/StackSwap"} call to replace
      it with a larger one, or simply set the global variable long
      __stack to a large enough value, if the startup code you link
      with provides stack swap support, as for example the c.o of
      SAS/C 5.x and above does.

      Due to Intuition limitations, @{"IDCMP_GADGETUP" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/intuition.h/File" 838} messages are not
      fully supported. The IAddress will always point to the root
      layout object of the window, not the actual gadget the message
      originates from. Use GadgetID to distinguish between gadgets.
      When using tab cycle, @{"GADGETUP" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/iobsolete.h/File" 115} messages will be lost
      altogether. However, layout.gadget sends a notification for all
      gadgetups, containing the tags @{"GA_ID" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/gadgetclass.h/File" 87}, @{"LAYOUT_RelVerify" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/gadgets/layout.h/File" 141} and
      @{"LAYOUT_RelCode" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/gadgets/layout.h/File" 144}, containing, respectively, the ID, @{"TRUE" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/exec/types.h/File" 95}, and the
      IntuiMessage.Code value it returned. Additionally a
      @{"LAYOUT_TabVerify" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/gadgets/layout.h/File" 184} tag will be @{"TRUE" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/exec/types.h/File" 95} or @{"FALSE" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/exec/types.h/File" 98} depending on whether
      the gadget release was triggered by tab cycle.
      Use of models and/or @{"IDCMP_IDCMPUPDATE" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/intuition.h/File" 856} is encouraged.

  SEE ALSO
      ReAction example source for usage.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "ActivateLayoutGadget" "layout_gc/ActivateLayoutGadget()"
@{b}

  NAME@{ub}
      @{"ActivateLayoutGadget" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/inline/layout.h/File" 30} -- Activate a gadget within a layout window.@{b}

  SYNOPSIS@{ub}
      Success = @{"ActivateLayoutGadget" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/inline/layout.h/File" 30}( Gadget, Window, Request, Object )
      d0                              a0      a1      a2       d0

      @{"BOOL" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/exec/types.h/File" 91} @{"ActivateLayoutGadget" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/inline/layout.h/File" 30}( @{"struct Gadget" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/intuition.h/File" 214} *, @{"struct Window" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/intuition.h/File" 909} *,
              @{"struct Requester" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/intuition.h/File" 144} *, @{"ULONG" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/exec/types.h/File" 52} );@{b}

  FUNCTION@{ub}
      The equivalent of @{"intuition.library" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/intuition/MAIN"} @{"ActivateGadget()" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/intuition/ActivateGadget"} for a
      window controlled by layout.gadget. If successful, this means
      that the user does not need to click in the gadget before
      typing.

      The gadget parameter MUST point to the root layout gadget in
      the window, and the object parameter to the gagdet you wish
      to activate. This works by calling the private
      LAYOUT_ACTIVATEOBJECT method to search the layout hierarchy for
      the specified gadget, and set the handleinput path to that
      gadget, and finally calling @{"ActivateGadget" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/intuition/ActivateGadget"} for the root object.

      The rules of calling @{"ActivateGadget()" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/intuition/ActivateGadget"} apply to
      @{"ActivateLayoutGadget" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/inline/layout.h/File" 30}() also.@{b}

  INPUTS@{ub}
      Gadget = pointer to the root layout obejct for the window.
      Window = pointer to the window the gadget is in.
      Requester = pointer to a requester (may be @{"NULL" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/exec/types.h/File" 101})
      Object = pointer to the BOOPSI object you wish to activate.@{b}

  RESULT@{ub}
      If the conditions above (and those of @{"ActivateGadget()" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/intuition/ActivateGadget"}) are
      met, the function will return @{"TRUE" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/exec/types.h/File" 95}, else @{"FALSE" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/exec/types.h/File" 98}.@{b}

  NOTES@{ub}
      Not only string gadgets can be activated this way. Many
      ReAction gadget classes, such as the button.gadget, also
      support keyboard control, and thus may be activated this way.

      An attempt to activate a gadget that is not currently visible
      (as on a hidden page) will fail.@{b}

  SEE ALSO@{ub}
      @{"intuition.library/ActivateGadget()" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/intuition/ActivateGadget"}

@ENDNODE
@NODE "FlushLayoutDomainCache" "layout_gc/FlushLayoutDomainCache()"
@{b}

  NAME@{ub}
      @{"FlushLayoutDomainCache" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/inline/layout.h/File" 34} -- Flush layout domain cache below a level.@{b}

  SYNOPSIS@{ub}
      @{"FlushLayoutDomainCache" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/inline/layout.h/File" 34}( layout )
                              a0

      void @{"FlushLayoutDomainCache" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/inline/layout.h/File" 34}( @{"struct Gadget" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/intuition.h/File" 214} * )@{b}

  FUNCTION@{ub}
      Layout gadget normally caches @{"GM_DOMAIN" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/gadgetclass.h/File" 323} results from the child
      objects to speed up window re-layout. However, on some rare
      occassions a gadget's minimum or maximum domain might change
      after creation. For these instances layout gadget provides two
      methods of controlling the domain cache. You can set a caching on
      a child-by-child basis, using the @{"CHILD_CacheDomain" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/gadgets/layout.h/File" 296} attribute, so
      that on each relayout the domain is calculated again. This
      method might have an extra performance hit, if the domain
      changes infrequently. It also has to be set for each parent
      layout level, which makes the amount of extra calculations grow
      quickly. The other method, for the cases where the application
      will know when a gadget's domain changes, it can call
      @{"FlushLayoutDomainCache" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/inline/layout.h/File" 34}() with a pointer to the parent layout object.
      This call will flush the whole hierarchy, so that the next window
      re-layout will re-calculate child domains.@{b}

  INPUTS@{ub}
      layout = the layout object to flush. This should be the topmost
                  layout object for the window.@{b}

  SEE ALSO@{ub}
      --datasheet-- (@{"CHILD_CacheDomain" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/gadgets/layout.h/File" 296} attribute)

@ENDNODE
@NODE "LAYOUT_GetClass" "layout_gc/LAYOUT_GetClass()"
@{b}

  NAME@{ub}
      @{"LAYOUT_GetClass" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/inline/layout.h/File" 26} -- Gets the pointer to the layout class.@{b}

  SYNOPSIS@{ub}
      layout_class = @{"LAYOUT_GetClass" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/inline/layout.h/File" 26}();
      D0

      Class * @{"LAYOUT_GetClass" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/inline/layout.h/File" 26}(@{"VOID" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/exec/types.h/File" 24});@{b}

  FUNCTION@{ub}
      Obtains the pointer to the layout gadget class for use with
      @{"NewObject()" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/intuition/NewObject"}.  This function always returns a valid pointer so
      you do not need to check it.  The reason is that if the library
      opens fine, then the pointer returned is already setup.  (Of
      course this implies that if opening the library fails, you
      shouldn't be calling this.)

      Note that this function does not create the class, that is done
      when the class library is opened.@{b}

  INPUTS@{ub}
      Nothing.@{b}

  RESULT@{ub}
      LayoutClass - Pointer to the layout gadget class.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "LayoutLimits" "layout_gc/LayoutLimits()"
@{b}

  NAME@{ub}
      @{"LayoutLimits" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/inline/layout.h/File" 42} -- easy way to find out max and min size of layout@{b}

  SYNOPSIS@{ub}
      @{"LayoutLimits" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/inline/layout.h/File" 42}( layout, limits, font, screen );
                    a0      a1      a2    a3

      void @{"LayoutLimits" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/inline/layout.h/File" 42}( @{"struct Gadget" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/intuition.h/File" 214} *, @{"struct LayoutLimits" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/gadgets/layout.h/File" 42} *,
                              @{"struct TextFont" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/graphics/text.h/File" 89} *, @{"struct Screen" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/screens.h/File" 133} * )@{b}

  FUNCTION@{ub}
      This function is an easy way of getting the minimum and maximum
      limit of the layout group. Effectively it create a RastPort and
      execute the @{"GM_DOMAIN" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/gadgetclass.h/File" 323} method for both minimum and maximum size
      of the object filling in the @{"LayoutLimits" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/inline/layout.h/File" 42} structure with the size
      values. The font passed to this call will most likely affect the
      results, so use the font you will use with the window. If you
      pass a @{"NULL" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/exec/types.h/File" 101} for the font, the system default font (monospaced)
      will be used. If you pass the optional screen pointer, the
      gadget will be provided a DrawInfo. This will let the gadget
      adjust to the aspect ratio of the screen.

      If you use the resulting size for @{"OpenWindow()" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/intuition/OpenWindow"} or @{"WindowLimits()" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/intuition/WindowLimits"},
      remember that the results do not include window borders.@{b}

  INPUTS@{ub}
      layout = the layout object to get the size on.
      limits = a pointer to the @{"struct LayoutLimits" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/gadgets/layout.h/File" 42} to fill.
      font = the TextFont to use on the domain requests. May be @{"NULL" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/exec/types.h/File" 101}
              for system default font.
      screen = optional pointer to the screen on which the layout
              will be used on, or @{"NULL" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/exec/types.h/File" 101}.@{b}

  NOTES@{ub}
      This function will invoke the object's @{"GM_DOMAIN" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/gadgetclass.h/File" 323} method twice,
      with a @{"NULL" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/exec/types.h/File" 101} GadgetInfo. If you call it providing a screen
      pointer, the taglist of the message will contain that screen's
      DrawInfo (@{"GA_DrawInfo" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/gadgetclass.h/File" 159}) for aspect information.@{b}

  SEE ALSO@{ub}
      gadgetclass/@{"GM_DOMAIN" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/gadgetclass.h/File" 323}

@ENDNODE
@NODE "RethinkLayout" "layout_gc/RethinkLayout()"
@{b}

  NAME@{ub}
      @{"RethinkLayout" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/inline/layout.h/File" 38} -- Relayout and render the layout. (V39)@{b}

  SYNOPSIS@{ub}
      @{"RethinkLayout" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/inline/layout.h/File" 38}( layout, window, requester, refresh );
                      a0        a1        a2

      void @{"RethinkLayout" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/inline/layout.h/File" 38}( @{"struct Gadget" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/intuition.h/File" 214} *, @{"struct Window" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/intuition.h/File" 909} *,
                              @{"struct Requester" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/intuition.h/File" 144} *, @{"BOOL" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/exec/types.h/File" 91} )@{b}

  FUNCTION@{ub}
      Relayout and refresh the layout page. Call this function after
      a call @{"SetGadgetAttrs()" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/intuition/SetGadgetAttrsA"} returns 1 to display the changes in the
      layout.  According to BOOPSI rules, a gadget will return a value
      of 1 from @{"OM_SET" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/classusr.h/File" 65} to tell the application to refresh. This is what
      this function is for. Basically, it will call the @{"GM_LAYOUT" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/gadgetclass.h/File" 318} and
      @{"GM_RENDER" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/intuition/gadgetclass.h/File" 302} methods of the layout.@{b}

  INPUTS@{ub}
      layout = the layout to refresh. Doesn't have to be the topmost
                  object in the hierarchy, if the changes do not affect
                  it.
      window = the window to which the layout (or its parent) is
                  attached to.
      requester = the window's requester, or @{"NULL" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/exec/types.h/File" 101}.
      refresh = whether layout.gadget should also refresh the display.@{b}

  NOTES@{ub}
      This function emulates a @{"DoGadgetMethod()" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/intuition/DoGadgetMethodA"} on V37 and V38 systems.

      The refresh flag is provided for several reasons. First, when using
      @{"LAYOUT_DeferLayout" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/gadgets/layout.h/File" 152}, you should not refresh upon receiving a
      @{"LAYOUT_RequestLayout" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/gadgets/layout.h/File" 157} notification. Second, datatypes have an
      asynchronous layout, and should not be attempted to refresh before
      that is finished. Wait for @{"DTA_Sync" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/Include/datatypes/datatypesclass.h/File" 117}, and then @{"RefreshGList" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/intuition/RefreshGList"}( layout,
      window, requester, 1 ).@{b}

  SEE ALSO@{ub}
      @{"intuition.library/RefreshGList()" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/intuition/RefreshGList"}, @{"intuition.library/SetGadgetAttrsA()" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/intuition/SetGadgetAttrsA"},
      @{"intuition.library/DoGadgetMethod()" LINK "gg:doc/NDK/Guide/intuition/DoGadgetMethodA"}

@ENDNODE
